column316:
The Japanese Garden is a park located in Sector 31 in union territory of Chandigarh. Built in 2014 on 13 acres of Land, by Indian Government, it was inaugurated by Shivraj Patil on 7 November 2014. It consists of water bodies, pagoda towers, water falls, meditation centre, a buddha idol and golden bamboos. This is first ever garden in Chandigarh with Japanese touch. The garden has been developed at a cost of Rs 6 crore.

The Japanese Garden consists of two phases. The Phase-1 was inaugurated on 7 November 2014 and the Phase-2 of the park was opened to public on 4 June 2016. Both the phases of the park are connected by a tunnel decorated by beautiful Japanese paintings on both sides. The garden is designed using Japanese architecture and each of the elements in the garden is given a unique Japanese touch.

Rotary Peace Monument at Sukhna Lake.

Rotary Club of Chandigarh has set up a Rotary Peace Monument at Sukhna Lake.

On 12 December 2003, Rotary International President Jonathan B. Majiyagbe had formally unveiled the monument and handed it over to His Excellency Justice O.P. Verma, the Governor of Punjab and Administrator UT, Chandigarh, after Rotary International had declared Chandigarh as ‘Rotary Peace City’.

It consists of a monument with the symbolic open hand monument cut out in it.

column316:
It's an artificial lake but beautiful. You will have a serene experience some 200ms from the start point, just water, nature and you.

For experience, try boating with friends/family. Shikara ride for couples and it's a great first date activity.

Food options are also quite good. From South Indian, to Chinese and kulcha + bhelpuri vendors for street food experience.

For Kids; some rides and activities within the premises. The camel ride is also there outside the lake.

Sketch Artists are also present nearby food arena.

Birds, Nature is awesome.

Overall, it's a must visit whenever you are in Chandigarh.

Bonus Tip: Rock Garden and Bird Park is nearby (5 mins) and definitely worth visiting.

column336:
The lake was created by Le Corbusier and the Chief Engineer P L Verma. To preserve its tranquility, Corbusier insisted on two things: that it be forbidden for motor boats to circulate in the water, and for vehicular traffic to be prohibited on top of the dam (promenade). The lake is fringed by a golf course to the south, and Nek Chand's famous Rock Garden of Chandigarh to its west.
The lake is facing serious issues like weed overgrowth, catchment adequacy  and silting that are significantly shrinking its size and depth. A project team, under Parasu Ram Mishra, was deployed to address the issue and take remedial measures, which halted the sedimentation, for a while. Additionally, it has become the subject of litigation between Chandigarh and Punjab.

column316: Chhatbir Zoo, is a zoological park situated close to Zirakpur, India. The entry ticket for adults is 100rs  and for kids 50rs. The best experience is lion safari which is for 15 minutes at price of 75rs. The zoo is well maintained. Many wild animals can be found in the area. There are many water and bird species. Dinosaur park is good which contains models of different dinosaurs which move a little bit. There is a separate place for big birds which is quite amazing as birds are free to move in that particular area. Reptile house is good but there are less species. There is canteen at every 5 minute’s walking. Overall a great place to spend a day with kids and it will usually take you 3-5 hours easily.

Jawahar lal Nehru etc. Besides this various showcase items like Nathu Ram Godse's handcuffs and a copy of original Constitution of India signed by Constituent committe and many old stamps of the era are also on display here.

column316:
The monument built in Chandigarh by Legendary Architect, Le Corbusier is Open Hand Monument.
The Open Hand Monument is a symbolic structure designed by the architect Le Corbusier and located in the Capitol Complex of the Indian city and union territory of Chandigarh.
It is the emblem and symbol of the Government of Chandigarh and symbolizes "the hand to give and the hand to take, peace and prosperity, and the unity of mankind".
The largest example of Le Corbusier's many Open Hand sculptures, it stands 26 meters high.
The metal structure with vanes is 14 meters high, weighs 50 short tons, and was designed to rotate in the wind.

As I stepped into the Terraced Garden in Chandigarh, I was immediately struck by the sheer beauty of the place. The garden was well-maintained and the display of flowers was simply stunning. I couldn't help but notice that there were so many flowers stacked together, which made the garden even more visually appealing.

As I walked through the garden, I could see that the flowers had been carefully selected and arranged in a way that was both aesthetically pleasing and structurally sound. The gardeners had clearly put a lot of thought and effort into creating this beautiful display.

In addition to the flowers, the garden also had several fountains and water features that added to its charm. The sound of the water added to the peaceful and serene atmosphere of the garden.

Overall, the Terraced Garden in Chandigarh is a must-visit attraction for anyone who loves nature and wants to enjoy a relaxing environment. The beauty and tranquility of the place make it a perfect escape from the hustle and bustle of the city.

column336:
Le Corbusier Centre is the place where the foundation of the City Beautiful was laid. Here you will find the first ever structure of Chandigarh. It is located in Sector 19 on Madhya Marg, one of the most easily accessible destinations.
This place is home to Le Corbusier Museum which is opened from 10am to 6pm (closed on Mondays). Also, this place is home to Chandigarh Lalit Kala Academy which is a favorite place for art lovers of the region.
In the backyard of this centre, a magnificent cafe is situated by the name Buns Bistro. This place offers peace and is a great destination to hold conversation over a coffee. They only let the entry through prior table reservation.
One may face a bit of parking issue during busy time.

A very beautiful and serene place. Well maintained by the tourism board. I had the opportunity to visit during a rainy day which showered the garden with a whole new charm and tranquility.

I suggest visiting in the early mornings and explore the area. Chandigarh's very special garden with its unique and boundless array of roses, well taken care of. A small stream of water flows right through the middle of the garden and can be crosses over on a mini bridge. A good place for people of all age groups. A must visit when in Chandigarh.

column336: Zakir Hussain Rose Garden is very nice and special place to visit in Chandigarh. The garden is very well maintained and you will be amazed to see the different varieties and colours of roses. This is the largest Rose Garden in Asia and is spread over an area of 40 acres and has more than 32,500 plants representing around 825 varieties of roses. This is nice place if you want to spend some time in peace. However the flowering season is mostly in summers so in winters the flowering is scarce. Kids also have a play area inside the garden so they can equally enjoy. Rose festival here is very popular. Must visit this place.
column427: Spread over an area of 30 acre, this is Asia's largest rose garden that has been named after India's former President, Zakir Hussain.

The place is wonderfully designed.
There are many things to explore inside, like The Doll museum,  laughing mirrors, a small aquarium, and big swings.

The rock structures are beautifully craved and are a delight to watch.

There are many places to take good pictures.

Be very careful of your head as the gates are very low.

You need atleast 2 hours to explore the place completely.

Great place to bring your family and children for a fun day.

The parking is chargeable.
